# 🔐 Secure MCP Tunnel

Organizations often keep MCP servers inside private networks or behind firewalls.

**Secure MCP Tunnel** creates an encrypted outbound connection that allows supported OpenAI products to communicate with a private MCP server without exposing it to the public internet.

### Architecture

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    P[Private MCP Server]
    T[Secure MCP Tunnel]
    O[OpenAI]

    P --> T
    T -->|Encrypted Connection| O
```

---

# 🔌 Connectors

**Connectors** are OpenAI-maintained MCP integrations for commonly used third-party services.

Instead of providing a custom `server_url`, developers specify a predefined `connector_id`.

Examples include:

* Gmail
* Google Drive
* Google Calendar
* Dropbox
* Outlook Email
* Outlook Calendar
* Microsoft Teams
* SharePoint

Connectors use the same MCP interface as Remote MCP servers but are managed by OpenAI, making them easier to configure and maintain.

---

# 📊 Local MCP vs Remote MCP

| Feature           | Local MCP                     | Remote MCP                              |
| ----------------- | ----------------------------- | --------------------------------------- |
| Server Location   | Local machine                 | Remote server or cloud                  |
| Communication     | stdio                         | HTTP / HTTP-SSE / Streamable HTTP       |
| Internet Required | Usually No                    | Yes                                     |
| Authentication    | Usually not required          | OAuth / API Tokens                      |
| Performance       | Very low latency              | Depends on network latency              |
| Data Privacy      | Data remains on local machine | Data is transmitted to remote server    |
| Deployment        | Local installation            | Public endpoint or Secure MCP Tunnel    |
| Best For          | Local files, IDEs, databases  | Cloud services, enterprise applications |

---

# 🔄 MCP Workflow

Regardless of whether the server is local or remote, the workflow is similar.

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant User
    participant AI
    participant MCP Server
    participant External Tool

    User->>AI: Ask a question
    AI->>MCP Server: List available tools
    MCP Server-->>AI: Tool definitions
    AI->>MCP Server: Call selected tool
    MCP Server->>External Tool: Execute request
    External Tool-->>MCP Server: Return result
    MCP Server-->>AI: Tool output
    AI-->>User: Final response
```

---

